******
[1] Guinea: suspected cases
- New Ebola cases suspected in West Africa's Guinea
Date: Sat 13 Feb 2021
Source: All Africa [abridged, edited]
https://africatimes.com/2021/02/13/new-ebola-cases-suspected-in-west-africas-guinea/


New cases of the Ebola virus are now suspected in the West African nation of Guinea, according to the country's health minister.

The latest report from Agence France Presse put the death toll there at 4 people, noting these are the 1st cases of Ebola in Guinea since 2016. Local reports put the death toll at 3, with a small cluster of cases emerging in the community of Gouecke in the country's south. Gouecke and nearby hub Nzerekore are not far from the borders with Liberia and Cote d'Ivoire.

Health Minister Remy Lamah said at least one patient was taken to Conakry for treatment rather than kept in isolation in Nongo, a cause for concern as officials wait for a 2nd set of results to confirm the Ebola infections.

Lamah promised a more comprehensive statement when those tests, which are in progress, are available.

At least 2 of the cases were confirmed by initial lab results, according to hospital employees speaking with local reporters.

The early reports from Guinea come as officials in the Democratic Republic of Congo announced a 3rd case of a reemerging Ebola virus outbreak in the country's volatile east.

The World Health Organization said this case was confirmed in Katwa, just a few kilometers east of Butembo and the 1st new case reported earlier this week. The new cases have emerged since Congolese officials declared an end to Ebola in June 2020, after an outbreak that claimed 2300 lives, many of them in Katwa and Butembo.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[This latest report on possibly 4 cases in Guinea is disturbing since it implies that the virus has now spread more than 2000 miles beyond the location of the initial cases in the DRC.

The epidemic of Ebola virus disease in Guinea from 2013-2016 represented the 1st ever outbreak of Ebola in a West African country. Previous outbreaks had been confined to Sub-Saharan Africa.

The epidemic, which began with the death of a 2-year-old boy, was part of a larger Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa which spread through Guinea and the neighboring countries of Liberia and Sierra Leone, with minor outbreaks occurring in Senegal, Nigeria, and Mali. In December 2015, Guinea was declared free of Ebola transmission by the U.N. World Health Organization; however, further cases continued to be reported from March 2016. The country was again declared as Ebola-free in June 2016 (Wikipedia). - Mod.LK]

------
- Nzerekore: 4 fatal cases
Date: Sat 13 Feb 2021
Source: The Guardian [abridged, edited]
https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/feb/13/ebola-kills-four-in-guinea-in-first-resurgence-of-disease-in-five-years


Ebola has killed 4 in Guinea in its 1st resurgence of disease in years. The Health Minister says officials are "really concerned" about deaths in the south-east region Nzerekore.

One of the latest victims in Guinea was a nurse who fell ill in late January 2021 and was buried on 1 Feb 2021, National Health Security Agency head Sakoba Keita told local media. "Among those who took part in the burial, 8 people showed symptoms: diarrhoea, vomiting and bleeding," he said. "Three of them died, and 4 others are in hospital."

The 4 deaths from Ebola hemorrhagic fever occurred in the south-east region of Nzerekore, he said.

Ebola also killed a woman in Democratic Republic of Congo, the health ministry says.

Keita also told local media that one patient had "escaped" but had been found and hospitalised in the capital Conakry. He confirmed the comments to AFP without giving further details.

The World Health Organization has eyed each new outbreak since 2016 with great concern, treating the most recent one in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) as an international health emergency.

DRC has faced several outbreaks of the illness, with the WHO confirming a resurgence 3 months after authorities declared the end of the country's latest outbreak.

The country had declared the 6-month epidemic over in November 2021. It was the country's 11th Ebola outbreak, claiming 55 lives out of 130 cases.

The widespread use of vaccinations, which were administered to more than 40 000 people, helped curb the disease.

The 2013-16 outbreak sped up the development of a vaccine against Ebola, with a global emergency stockpile of 500 000 doses planned to respond quickly to future outbreaks, the vaccine alliance Gavi said in January 2021.

