[The 4 suspected cases reported above are reported fatal here. It is hoped virus is being sequenced to confirm connection between the cases in the DRC and these in Guinea. - Mod.LK]

------
- Nzerekore prefecture: 8 cases suspected
Date: Sat 13 Feb 2021
Source: Guinee News [Google trans. edited]
https://www.guineenews.org/cas-suspects-debola-en-guinee-lanss-precise/


Following a burial, 8 cases of diarrhea, vomiting and bleeding were reported, including 3 deaths in the sub-prefecture of Goueke, 45 km from N'Zerekore.

Samples [from patients with haemorrhagic fever] were taken and sent to the Labs of Gueckedou and Conakry. Four patients have been isolated at the CTEPI in N'Zerekore since 11 Feb 2021, and one in Conakry on 12 Feb 2021.

The Gueckedou lab provided a 1st result revealing the presence of the Ebolavirus. A 2nd confirmation is underway at the hemorrhagic fever laboratory in Conakry.

Case history information:
A nurse from the Goueke health center fell ill; she was examined by the head of the center and referred to N'Zerekore center; she died between 27 and 28 Jan 2021. His burial took place on 1 Feb 2021 in Goueke. She was among the people who took part in the funeral that these 8 cases were counted from.

Measures taken:
Isolation of all suspected cases at CTEPI N'Zerekore and Conakry; Case investigation to clarify data, identify other suspected cases, and identify and isolate all contacts (an investigative mission left for Goueke on 13 Feb 2021); Initiate steps to acquire vaccines against Ebola from WHO and CDC with a view to possibly carrying out a ring vaccination in the affected areas.

A declaration will be made upon re-confirmation.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Unsafe practices at the burial likely led to the 8 cases, who were all in attendance. Education programs will need to be reinitiated along with vaccination of contacts. One has to worry about the spread from other casual contacts who have not been identified. - Mod.LK]

******
[2] DRC (North Kivu): virus transmission via semen
Date: Fri 12 Feb 2021
Source: IFL Science [abridged, edited]
https://www.iflscience.com/health-and-medicine/ebola-can-lurk-in-semen-for-more-than-a-year-could-this-explain-a-new-outbreak/


Ref. MJ Soka*, MJ Choi*, A Baller et al. Prevention of sexual transmission of Ebola in Liberia through a national semen testing and counselling programme for survivors: an analysis of Ebola virus RNA results and behavioural data. Lancet Glob Health 2016; 4: e736-43. Published Online 30 Aug 2016 http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/ S2214-109X(16)30175-9.
------------------------------
There are fears of a new Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) after the country has been hit with new cases of the disease.

It's known that Ebola can linger in bodily fluids, namely semen, for over a year after the initial infection. A 2016 study published in the Lancet Global Health found that 24 out of 429 men in Liberia tested positive for Ebola in their semen at least 12 months after they'd recovered from the disease. In one of the men, Ebola virus RNA was detected in the semen 565 days after recovery from the infection.

The disease can also be spread by having contact with urine, saliva, sweat, feces, vomit, breast milk, and amniotic fluid of a person who is sick with or who has died from Ebola virus disease. Additionally, the virus is still present in animal reservoirs in the region.

The WHO is also investigating whether the new case is linked to "a new spillover event" or whether it is a resurgence of the outbreak that ran from 2018 to 2020.

"Samples have been sent to the National Institute of Biomedical Research in Kinshasa, #DRC for genome sequencing to determine a link to the previous outbreak. It is not unusual for sporadic cases to occur following a major outbreak," tweeted WHO African Region.

Ebola is a viral disease that causes problems with how your blood clots and is often fatal if left untreated. Around half the people who contract the disease die, although case fatality rates have varied from 25 percent to 90 percent in different outbreaks. The infection often starts with symptoms such as fever, fatigue, muscle pains, and is followed by vomiting, diarrhea, impaired kidney and liver function, and unexplained bleeding. Fortunately, effective Ebola vaccines have been developed in recent years and were extensively used in the 2018-2020 DRC outbreak.

The 2014-2016 Ebola outbreak in West Africa was the deadliest outbreak of the disease in history, with more than 28 600 cases and 11 325 deaths, primarily in Guinea, Liberia, and Sierra Leone. The 2018-2020 Ebola outbreak in the DRC was responsible for around 3470 cases and 2280 deaths. Like many countries that have dealt with severe disease outbreaks, the DRC has noted that their experience with Ebola taught them some important lessons about how to prepare for COVID-19.

"DRC is now better, smarter, and faster at responding to Ebola, and this is an enduring legacy that is supporting the response to COVID-19 and other outbreaks," Matshidiso Moeti, WHO regional director for Africa, said in a statement last year [2020].

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Anxiously awaiting sequencing results, which will clarify whether the virus circulating is from a new spillover event or transmission from husband to wife. Either way, the response is now in action to control spread. But the latest case in Guinea is concerning since it demonstrates cases of the virus beyond the borders of DRC. - Mod.LK

